\title{cardinality of the cartesian product}
\date{2024-01-28}
\author{jonmsterling}
\taxon{example}
\import{jms-00JB}

\p{For all #{m,n\in\mathbb{N}}, we have #{\brk{m}\times\brk{n} \cong \brk{m\cdot n}}.}

\p{We can prove this from a combinatoric point of view.}

\proof{
 \p{To choose a pair #{\prn{i,j}\in\brk{m}\times\brk{n}}, we first choose an element of \brk{m} and we second choose an element of #{\brk{n}}. There are #{m} possibilities for the first choice and #{n} possibilities for the second choice; as these choices are independent, we simply have #{m\cdot n} choices in total.}
}

\p{We can also prove this isomorphism more formally by means of a specific bijection.}

\proof{
 \p{We can think of the cartesian product #{\brk{m}\times\brk{n}} as the set of cells in table or matrix with #{m} columns and #{n} rows â€” and then an element \prn{i,j} with #{i\in\brk{m}} and #{j\in\brk{n}} is the coordinate of a given cell. Naturally, the total number of cells would be #{m\cdot n}, but we can prove this formally by constructing the function that takes a coordinate \prn{i,j} to its absolute index in the counting of cells from left to right and top to bottom:}

 ##{
  \begin{aligned}
   I &\colon\brk{m}\times\brk{n}\to \brk{m\cdot n}\\
   I\prn{i,j} &= m\cdot j + i
  \end{aligned}
 }
}

\p{We do need to check that #{I\prn{i,j}< m\cdot n} for all #{i<m} and #{j<n}. The maximimum value of #{I} is naturally #{I\prn{m-1,n-1}}:}

##{
 \begin{aligned}
  I\prn{m-1,n-1} &= m\cdot\prn{n-1} + \prn{m-1}
  \\
  &=
  m\cdot n - m + m - 1
  \\
  &=
  m\cdot n - 1
  \\
  &< m\cdot n
 \end{aligned}
}

\p{The inverse function #{I\inv\colon\brk{m\cdot n}\to\brk{m}\times\brk{n}} takes #{i<m\cdot n} to the pair \prn{\operatorname{rem}\prn{i,m}, \operatorname{quo}\prn{i,m}}.}